(87, 1, '2011-07-28 05:28:24', '2011-07-28 05:28:24', 'from Â <a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html">http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html</a>\n<table width="610" border="0" align="center">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td align="right" valign="bottom" width="81%">\n<div align="left"><span style="font-family: Arial; font-size: x-small;"><strong>Chapter 2</strong></span>\n<span style="color: #b50800; font-family: Arial; font-size: large;"><strong>How weÂ <em>really</em>Â use the Web\n</strong></span></div></td>\n<td align="right" valign="top" width="13%">\n<div align="right"><span style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: x-small;"><span style="color: #6699cc; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: medium;"><strong><img src="http://www.sensible.com/DMMT%20cover%203d%20140h.jpg" alt="" width="54" height="70" align="top" /></strong></span><span style="font-size: xx-small;">Â </span><strong></strong></span></div></td>\n<td align="left" valign="top" width="3%"></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table width="610" border="0" align="center">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width="27"></td>\n<td width="540">\n<blockquote>\n<div align="right"><span style="font-size: small;"><em>\nWhy are things always in the last place you look for them?\nBecause you stop looking when you find them.</em>\nâ€”Childrenâ€™s riddle</span></div></blockquote>\nIn the past five years Iâ€™ve spent a lot of time watching people use the Web, and the thing that has struck me most is the difference between how we think people use Web sites and how they actually use them.\n\nWhen weâ€™re creating sites, we act as though people are going to pore over each page, reading our finely crafted text, figuring out how weâ€™ve organized things, and weighing their options before deciding which link to click.\n\nWhat they actually do most of the time (if weâ€™re lucky) isÂ <em>glance</em>Â at each new page, scan<em>some</em>Â of the text, and click on the first link that catches their interest or vaguely resembles the thing theyâ€™re looking for. There are usually large parts of the page that they donâ€™t even look at.\n\nWeâ€™re thinking â€œgreat literatureâ€ (or at least â€œproduct brochureâ€), while the userâ€™s reality is much closer to â€œbillboard going by at 60 miles an hour.â€\n<p align="CENTER"><img src="http://www.sensible.com/sc%201.gif" alt="What we design for vs. The reality" width="445" height="233" /></p>\nAs you might imagine, itâ€™s a little more complicated than this, and it depends on the kind of page, what the user is trying to do, how much of a hurry sheâ€™s in, and so on. But this simplistic view is much closer to reality than most of us imagine.\n\nIt makes sense that we picture a more rational, attentive user when weâ€™re designing pages. Itâ€™s only natural to assume that everyone uses the Web the same way we do, andâ€”like everyone elseâ€”we tend to think that our own behavior is much more orderly and sensible than it really is.\n\nIf you want to design effective Web pages, though, you have to learn to live with three facts about real-world Web use.\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial; font-size: medium;">\n\nFact of life #1:Â </span>\n<span style="color: #b50800; font-family: Arial; font-size: large;"><strong>We donâ€™t read pages. We scan them.</strong></span>\n\n<a name="backfromfootnote1"></a>One of the very few well-documented facts about Web use is that people tend to spend very little timeÂ <em>reading</em>Â most Web pages.<a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#footnote1"><sup><strong>1</strong></sup></a>Â  Instead, we scan (or skim) them, looking for words or phrases that catch our eye.\n\nThe exception, of course, is pages that contain documents like news stories, reports, or product descriptions. But even then, if the document is longer than a few paragraphs, weâ€™re likely to print it outâ€”since itâ€™s easier and faster to read on paper than on a screen.\n\nWhy do we scan?\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Weâ€™re usually in a hurry.</strong>Â Much of our Web use is motivated by the desire to save time. As a result, Web users tend to act like sharks: they have to keep moving, or theyâ€™ll die. We just donâ€™t have the time to read any more than necessary.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>We know we donâ€™tÂ <em>need</em>Â to read everything.</strong>Â On most pages, weâ€™re really only interested in a fraction of whatâ€™s on the page. Weâ€™re just looking for the bits that match our interests or the task at hand, and the rest of it is irrelevant. Scanning is how we find the relevant bits.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Weâ€™re good at it.</strong>Â Weâ€™ve been scanning newspapers, magazines, and books all our lives to find the parts weâ€™re interested in, and we know that it works.</li>\n</ul>\nThe net effect is a lot like Gary Larsonâ€™s classic Far Side cartoon about the difference between what we say to dogs and what they hear. In the cartoon, the dog (named Ginger) appears to be listening intently as her owner gives her a serious talking-to about staying out of the garbage. But from the dogâ€™s point of view, all heâ€™s saying is â€œblah blah GINGER blah blah blah blah GINGER blah blah blah.â€\n\nWhat we see when we look at a Web page depends on what we have in mind, but itâ€™s usually just a fraction of whatâ€™s on the page.\n\n&nbsp;\n<p align="CENTER"><img src="http://www.sensible.com/sc%202.gif" alt="What designers build vs. What users see" width="445" height="244" /></p>\nLike Ginger, we tend to focus on words and phrases that seem to match (a) the task at hand or (b) our current or ongoing personal interests. And of course, (c) the trigger words that are hardwired into our nervous systems, like â€œFree,â€ â€œSale,â€ and â€œSex.â€\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial; font-size: medium;">\n\nFact of life #2:Â </span>\n<span style="color: #b50800; font-family: Arial; font-size: large;"><strong>We donâ€™t make optimal choices.\nWe satisfice.</strong></span>\n\nWhen weâ€™re designing pages, we tend to assume that users will scan the page, consider all of the available options, and choose the best one.\n\n<a name="backfromfootnote2"></a>In reality, though, most of the time weÂ <em>donâ€™t</em>Â choose the best optionâ€”we choose theÂ <em>first reasonable option</em>, a strategy known as satisficing.<a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#footnote2"><sup><strong>2</strong></sup></a>Â  As soon as we find a link that seems like it might lead to what weâ€™re looking for, thereâ€™s a very good chance that weâ€™ll click it.\n\n<a name="backfromfootnote3"></a>Iâ€™d observed this behavior for years, but its significance wasnâ€™t really clear to me until I read Gary Kleinâ€™s book,Â <em>Sources of Power: How People Make Decisions</em>.<a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#footnote3"><sup><strong>3</strong></sup></a>Â  Klein has spent fifteen years studying naturalistic decision making: how people like fire fighters, pilots, chess masters, and nuclear power plant operators make high-stakes decisions in real settings, with time pressure, vague goals, limited information, and changing conditions.\n\nKleinâ€™s team of observers went into their first study (of field commanders at fire scenes) with the generally accepted model of rational decision making: faced with a problem, a person gathers information, identifies the possible solutions, and chooses the best one. They started with the hypothesis that because of the high stakes and extreme time pressure, fire captains would be able to compare only two options, an assumption they thought was conservative. As it turned out, the fire commanders didnâ€™t compareÂ <em>any</em>options. They took the first reasonable plan that came to mind and did a quick mental test for problems. If they didnâ€™t find any, they had their plan of action.\n\nSo why donâ€™t Web users look for the best choice?\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Weâ€™re usually in a hurry</strong>. And as Klein points out â€œOptimizing is hard, and it takes a long time. Satisficing is more efficient.â€</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Thereâ€™s not much of a penalty for guessing wrong.</strong>Â Unlike the firefighters, the penalty for guessing wrong on a Web site is usually only a click or two of the Back button, making satisficing an effective strategy. Of course, this assumes that pages load quickly; when they donâ€™t, we have to make our choices more carefullyâ€”just one of the many reasons why most Web users donâ€™t like slow-loading pages.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Weighing options may not improve our chances.Â </strong>On poorly designed sites, putting effort into making the best choice doesnâ€™t really help. Youâ€™re usually better off going with your first guess and using the Back button if it doesnâ€™t work out.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Guessing is more fun.</strong>Â Itâ€™s less work than weighing options, and if you guess right, itâ€™s faster. And it introduces an element of chanceâ€”the pleasant possibility of running into something surprising and good.</li>\n</ul>\nOf course, this is not to say that users never weigh options before they click. It depends on things like their frame of mind, how pressed they are for time, and how much confidence they have in the site.\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial; font-size: medium;">\n\nFact of life #3:Â </span>\n<span style="color: #b50800; font-family: Arial; font-size: large;"><strong>We donâ€™t figure out how things work.\nWe muddle through.</strong></span>\n\nOne of the things that becomes obvious as soon as you do any usability testingâ€”whether youâ€™re testing Web sites, software, or household appliancesâ€”is the extent to which people use things all the time without understanding how they work, or with completely wrong-headed ideas about how they work.\n\nFaced with any sort of technology, very few people take the time to read instructions. Instead, we forge ahead and muddle through, making up our own vaguely plausible stories about what weâ€™re doing and why it works.\n\n<img src="http://www.sensible.com/sc%203.gif" alt="The Prince and the Pauper (Classics Illustrated)" width="168" height="150" align="RIGHT" />It often reminds me of the scene at the end ofÂ <em>The Prince and the Pauper</em>Â where the real prince discovers that the look-alike pauper has been using the Great Seal of England as a nutcracker in his absence. (It makes perfect senseâ€”to him, the seal is just this great big, heavy chunk of metal.)\n\nAnd the fact is, we get things done that way. Iâ€™ve seen lots of people use software and Web sites effectively in ways that are nothing like what the designers intended.\n\n<a name="backfromfootnote4"></a>My favorite example is the people (and Iâ€™ve seen dozens of them myself) who will type a siteâ€™s entire URL in the Yahoo search box every time they want to go to thereâ€”not just to find the site for the first time, but every time they want to go there, sometimes several times a day. If you ask them about it, it becomes clear that some of them think that Yahoo<em>is</em>Â the Internet, and that this is the way you use it.<a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#footnote4"><sup><strong>4</strong></sup></a>\n<p align="CENTER"><img src="http://www.sensible.com/sc%204.gif" alt="Users type URLs in Yahoo''s search box" width="423" height="112" /></p>\nAnd muddling through is not limited to beginners. Even technically savvy users often have surprising gaps in their understanding of how things work. (I wouldnâ€™t be surprised if even Bill Gates has some bits of technology in his life that he uses by muddling through.)\n\nWhy does this happen?\n\n<strong><a name="backfromfootnote5"></a></strong>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Itâ€™s not important to us.Â </strong>For most of us, it doesnâ€™t matter to us whether we understand how things work, as long as we can use them. Itâ€™s not for lack of intelligence, but for lack of caring. In the great scheme of things, itâ€™s just not important to us.<a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#footnote5"><sup><strong>5</strong></sup></a></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>If we find something that works, we stick to it.</strong>Â Once we find something that worksâ€”no matter how badlyâ€”we tend not to look for a better way. Weâ€™ll use a better way if we stumble across one, but we seldom look for one.</li>\n</ul>\nItâ€™s always interesting to watch Web designers and developers observe their first usability test. The first time they see a user click on something completely inappropriate, theyâ€™re surprised. (For instance, when the user ignores a nice big fat â€œSoftwareâ€ button in the navigation bar, saying something like, â€œWell, Iâ€™m looking for software, so I guess Iâ€™d click here on â€˜Cheap Stuffâ€™ because cheap is always good.â€) The user may even find what heâ€™s looking for eventually, but by then the people watching donâ€™t know whether to be happy or not.\n\nThe second time it happens, theyâ€™re yelling â€œJust click on â€˜Softwareâ€™!â€ The third time, you can see them thinking: â€œWhy are we even bothering?â€\n\nAnd itâ€™s a good question: if people manage to muddle through so much, does it really matter whether they â€œget itâ€? The answer is that it matters a great deal because while muddling through may work sometimes, it tends to be inefficient and error prone. On the other hand, if users â€œget it,â€\n<ul>\n	<li>Thereâ€™s a much better chance that theyâ€™ll find what theyâ€™re looking for, which is good for them and for you.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Thereâ€™s a better chance that theyâ€™ll understand the full range of what your site has to offerâ€”not just the parts that they stumble across.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>You have a better chance of steering them to the parts of your site that you want them to see.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Theyâ€™ll feel smarter and more in control when theyâ€™re using your site, which will bring them back. You can only get away with a site that people muddle through until someone builds one down the street that makes them feel smart.</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>If life gives you lemons...</strong>\n\nBy now you may be thinking (given this less than rosy picture of the Web audience), â€œWhy donâ€™t I just get a job at the local 7-11? At least my effortsÂ <em>might</em>Â be appreciated.â€\n\nSo, whatâ€™s a girl to do?\n\nThe answer: if your audience is going to act like youâ€™re designing billboards, then design great billboards.\n<p align="CENTER">[The next chapter isÂ <em>Billboard Design 101</em>]</p>\n\n\n<hr align="LEFT" width="50%" />\n\n<a name="footnote1"></a><sup><strong>1</strong></sup>Â See Jakob Nielsenâ€™s October 1997 Alertbox column, â€œ<a href="http://useit.com/alertbox/9710a.html">How Users Read on the Web</a>â€ available at www.useit.com. Â <a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#backfromfootnote1"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">BACK</span></a>\n\n<a name="footnote2"></a><sup><strong>2</strong></sup>Â Economist Herbert Simon coined the term (a cross between satisfying and sufficing) in<em>Models of Man: Social and Rational</em>Â (Wiley, 1957). Â <a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#backfromfootnote2"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">BACK</span></a>\n\n<a name="footnote3"></a><sup><strong>3</strong></sup>Â The MIT Press, 1998. Â <a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#backfromfootnote3"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">BACK</span></a>\n\n<a name="footnote4"></a><sup><strong>4</strong></sup>Â In the same vein, Iâ€™ve encountered many AOL users who clearly think that AOL is the Internet. Good news for Yahoo and AOL. Â <a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#backfromfootnote4"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">BACK</span></a>\n\n<a name="footnote5"></a><sup><strong>5</strong></sup>Â Web developers often have a particularly hard time understandingâ€”or even believingâ€”that people might feel this way, since they themselves are usually keenly interested in how things work. Â <a href="http://www.sensible.com/chapter.html#backfromfootnote5"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">BACK</span></a>\n<p align="CENTER">Excerpted fromÂ <em>Donâ€™t Make Me Think! A Common Sense Approach to Web Usability</em>\nSecond Edition, New Riders Publishing\nÂ© 2005 Steve Krug</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>', 'How we really use the Web ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '86-revision', '', '', '2011-07-28 05:28:24', '2011-07-28 05:28:24', '', 86, 'http://third-law.com/86-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
