(126, 1, '2011-08-05 00:40:55', '2011-08-05 00:40:55', '<h2><a href="http://third-law.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/this-way-sign.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-123" title="this-way-sign" src="http://third-law.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/this-way-sign-300x199.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="199" /></a>Myth: People Don''t Read, They Scan</h2>\r\nOne way to attract people is to keep your posts short. The argument goes, "People don''t read, they scan". This is true to a certain degree, but rather than focusing on the magic length of a post, you ought to focus on the structure of your post. Design it to be interesting content wise as well as visually interesting.\r\n\r\nThe reason people scan when on the Web has little to do with length of a post. The act of scanning headlines, subheadlines and other emphasized text, is not a replacement for reading: itâ€™s just the first step of reading. We do this to find the most important information,Â quicklyÂ and efficiently. When we find what we are looking for, we begin to read, maybe just a paragraph, maybe the entire article.\r\n<h2>Write to Capture Scanners, Write Well to Capture Readers</h2>\r\nSo whether the article is short or long it needs to be easily scannable so your visitors can find what they are looking for and start reading. Headlines, subheadlines, bullet lists, etc. can all be used as a ways to help you visitors navigate to the content they are looking for.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>If you write a six paragraph article with nothing embellishing it, you may have just as well written nothing at all. Remember, your visitors need to be guided through your site and its content.</em></p>', 'People Do Scan and Then We Read', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '60-revision-v1', '', '', '2011-08-05 00:40:55', '2011-08-05 00:40:55', '', 60, 'http://third-law.com/60-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(127, 1, '2011-07-30 00:31:07', '2011-07-30 00:31:07', 'A friend asked me what I do all day as a web designer. I told him I stare at a computer screen and type in code that looks like pictures to everyone else. He sarcastically declared that I practiced witchcraft. I later learned thatÂ Arthur C. Clarke, the author of "2001: A Space Oddessy" shared my friend''sÂ assessment. In the last of Clarke''s three laws he stated,\r\n\r\n[quote type="center]Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic. [/quote]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThat is what I hope to do wit this web design firm. Do my job well enough that it comes across like a bit of magic. I want to accomplish that in my designs, the way the you interact with your site when you make changes, and my relationship with you as we build a web presence for your business.', 'Third Law Web Design', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '2-revision-4', '', '', '2011-07-30 00:31:07', '2011-07-30 00:31:07', '', 2, 'http://third-law.com/2-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
