(241, 1, '2011-09-23 01:29:40', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Sometimes we write in such a way that our wording itself becomes cluttered. These are phrases that a writer may use without even thinking. It is a second nature bad habit that creates posts that are only longer, but not higher in quality.\n<h3>Examples</h3>\nRather than "<em>in the amount of</em>Â ", you can simply use "for".Â Instead of using four words, you have reduced it down to one word that gets the job done. Rather than "<em>in the event of",</em>Â you can use "if". Â Phrases like inÂ <em>my opinion, as a matter of fact, type of</em>Â â€” just for example â€” can usually be cut entirely without changing the meaning of your sentence.\n\nMany writers use modifiers â€” adjectives and adverbs â€” throughout their content, thinking it will make their writing sparkle. But not all that sparkles is gold. Â Mark Twain wrote in a letter, regarding a friendâ€™s writing style, that he shouldnâ€™t â€œlet fluff and flowers and verbosity creep in. When you catch an adjective, kill it. No, I donâ€™t mean utterly, but kill most of them â€“ then the rest will be valuable. They weaken when they are close together.â€\n<h3>ADVERBS AND ADJECTIVES</h3>\nItâ€™s true. One specific, vivid adjective or adverb will do a better job communicating than two or three dull ones. Better still are precise nouns and verbs in the place of adjectives and adverbs. Take â€œHe slowly walked.â€ Slowly is an adverb and, no, thereâ€™s nothing technically wrong with that sentence, but did he walk slowly, or did he saunter? Maybe he ambled? Meandered? Donâ€™t those words feel a little more lively and clear than the original? Worse yet is â€œHe walkedÂ <em>very</em>Â slowly.â€ Very is a very favorite of new writers and itâ€™s almost always unnecessary clutter.\n\nThe same goes for adjectives. We really donâ€™t need to read more sentences about the â€œhot, bright sunâ€ because, frankly, we know the sun is usually hot and bright. If you feel you must use an adjective, tell us the sun is chilly or searing or something out of the ordinary (and even searing isnâ€™t that unusual) and you might pique my interest.\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Always try to choose words that will convey your meaning in the clearest, most concise and simplest way.</em></p>', 'Writing Clutter Free', '', 'draft', 'closed', 'open', '', 'clear-writing', '', '', '2011-09-23 01:29:40', '2011-09-23 01:29:40', '', 0, 'http://third-law.com/?p=241', 0, 'post', '', 0),
